== Step 2: Conflicting Requirements

**Checked pairs:**
- DR-4 (exactly one household admin) vs permission-rules-definition.adoc (Owner role)
- IR-03 (ownership specification) vs DR-6 (attribution retention)
- DR-12 (threshold low-stock) vs IR-04 (threshold definition)

|===
| Requirement A | Requirement B | Conflict Description | Which Should Win?
| DR-4: "Each Household shall have exactly one household admin role at a time"
| permission-rules-definition.adoc: "Owner: full permissions … Member: add/edit/delete items"
| DR-4 says exactly one admin role. permission-rules says Owner is admin-level, but also says Owners can transfer ownership and Member can become Owner. The doc does not specify if a household can have an Owner AND a separate admin role, or if Owner IS the admin.
| DR-4 should win. The domain requirement is authoritative. Clarify: "Owner = household admin. Only one Owner exists at a time. Transfer ownership changes who the admin is."

| IR-03: "mark an item as personal or shared, and if personal, associate it with a household member"
| DR-6: "Spending entries shall remain attributed to the household member who made the purchase, even when inventory quantities are reorganized"
| If a personal item is purchased by Member A but then marked as shared, should the spending entry stay attributed to Member A? Or become shared across household budget? IR-03 and DR-6 don't answer this.
| DR-6 should win. Financial history is immutable. Spending attribution never changes, even if item ownership changes later. Document this explicitly.

|===

**Note:** No direct conflict found between DR-12 and IR-04. They are complementary.

