=== 3. Equivalent requirements quality standard

The webinar mentioned MISRA/CERT for code (coding standards that prevent undefined behavior).

For requirements, the equivalent would be **EARS (Easy Approach to Requirements Syntax)** or **INCOSE Guide for Writing Requirements**.

**Suggested rules for a project requirements quality standard:**

.Suggested rules for a project requirements quality standard
|===
| Rule | Description | Example Violation

| 1. No subjective adjectives
| Avoid "fast," "easy," "quickly," "primarily," "initially"
| ❌ "The system shall respond quickly" +
  ✅ "The system shall respond within 500ms for 95% of requests"

| 2. One requirement per sentence
| No "ands" or "ors" combining multiple behaviors
| ❌ "The system shall deduplicate alerts and trigger them primarily on state transitions" +
  ✅ Split into two separate requirements

| 3. Testable in one sentence
| If you cannot describe how to test it in 10 words, rewrite it
| ❌ "The system shall be user-friendly" +
  ✅ "90% of new users complete onboarding without assistance"

| 4. No ambiguous quantifiers
| Avoid "some," "many," "several," "mostly," "primarily"
| ❌ "Most alerts shall be deduplicated" +
  ✅ "100% of alerts for unchanged states shall be suppressed"

| 5. Define all affordances
| If UI behavior is required, specify the interaction pattern
| ❌ "quick-edit affordance" +
  ✅ "inline pencil icon that opens an editable text field"
|===

